Pretty much everyone has had a "Love the way you lie" type relationship, whether it was physically violent or not, most of us have been trapped in that vicious cycle that you vow to end every single time, but can't.  I've been in two relationships like that. One violent one not, but the latter actually did more damage.  When I was in my very abusive relationship, it wasn't love that kept us there, but but obsessive, possessive co-dependant, feelings. It was like we were two of a kind, and we just fit. It felt like we belonged together in a fucked up kind of way.  The second time, it wasn't abusive, but it was crazy, deep, mad, love.... we hurt each other, but everytime either of us tried to leave, one of us would always stop the other from moving on, and each time, we'd get back together vowing to make it better, but it never was.  So many times, we knew it had to end for the sake of sanity, more than anything else....but everytime it seemed over, it wasn't and we'd just fall back into the same pattern, time after time.  Even my friends used to say "It's never going to end. Ever" and it felt like that for while.  After a while though, you become exhausted by it, and you accept that things are never going to change. It's heartbreaking, but such a relief at the same time.  I don't regret either of those relationships. The first because it gave me my little girl, and the second because, despite everything, he was, and is the best guy I've met, and I loved him, probably like I'll never love anyone, in a romantic sense,  again.  There is something in this song for every relationship. Some part(s) , or all, will always strike a cord for someone.

I want to prefice this comment by saying that I respect people's opinions.  I, as an atheist, love how Christians believe in God and Jesus, Heaven, Hell and so on but blindly ignore scientifically proven phenomena, such as the Big Bang and evolution. I find that even one of the greatest flaws in Christianity is stupidly obvious. Apparently, gambling is a sin but the fact that Christians base their lives on the probability that there are Heaven and Hell is hilariously hypocritical.  Next. Is there any proof whatsoever about anything stated in the Bible? Is there proof of an actual miracle? As someone with a great imagination, I keep an open mind to the possibility of magic. But. If it is so stupidly improbable, that it is not possible to be explained by science, then fine. Miracles may exist.  What  is wrong with listening to science, though? I understand that religion runs deep in a person's DNA but some things simply are simply not possible. They may be called miracles but to me, the are simply things born from the lack of understanding of the situation. As an example, let's take a human's survival after a very early birth. Is it easier to believe that God saved them or the doctors? God, naturally. But once again, the skills of the doctors are overshadowed by the "miracle" that God created. Because it is simpler to believe, even if it is stupidly obvious what really happened. Next, we have the stories in the Bible Take Noah's arc, for example. Are we expected to believe a human filled up a huge boat with 2 of each animal? What did they feed the lions? The tigers? Zebras? Even the most hardcore Christian has to agree that that is a bit too much to believe. Once again, I want to state that I respect people's beliefs and in no way wish to offend anybody. If you are interested in having a sensible conversation about anything I've said so far, have at it, but if you only want to scream: "Sinner!!!", " Burn in hell!!", "ATHEIST!!!", please go do it on Sunday in church, where people would listen.
